</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=syllestraefv>Syllestrae FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3556<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/26/03 12:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=688.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I hate the RIAA.  A lot.</span><hr size=1> I already agreed with you that it's theft.<br>
<br>
I just disagreed that it drives up the price for everyone else.<br>
<br>
If you steal McDonald's French Fries, whether you would have bought them or not, they lose actual physical material.  They lost those fries.<br>
<br>
When you steal music online, they only lose money if you would have otherwise bought that music.  If you never would have bought it, they don't lose anything tangible.<br>
<br>
It's like the guy who watches a drive-in movie from the roof of his house.  If he wouldn't have gone to the drive-in physically, they haven't lost <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>anything</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> from his free viewership of the movie.<br>
<br>
I'm not arguing in support of illegal downloading, just disagreeing with you that it necessarily causes a loss to the recording industry.  If I had to pull a number out of my ass, I would say that about 10 to 15 percent of music downloaded online would have actually been purchased had people not been able to get it for free.  I would guess the other 85 to 90 percent people like enough to download for free, but not enough to shell out 15 bucks for.<br>
<br>
- Syll <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dashanvaliant>DashanValiant</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 172<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/26/03 12:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=688.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Pirates, etc.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Especially because a person who downloads music they would never have bought has no impact whatsoever.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
However, this number is much smaller than those who *claim* they wouldn't have bought it if they couldn't have pirated it.  I had a roommate who pirated game CDs all the time; and we had this discussion once, and he kept saying he would never have bought any of the games he pirated.  However, he kept playing them and pirating them, so I found that to be a very dubious argument.  In truth, I believe most people, including him, pirate because they can, and while they *would* pay for the software/music/movie if they had to; if they can steal it, it's just as well because it is, as they see it, a victimless crime.  But really, it isn't.  I saw an interesting ad for &quot;stop movie piracy&quot; when I went to the movies this past weekend.  It was from a point of view of a set designer.  His point was essentially, &quot;I'm not a multi-million dollar star.  I'm not a highly paid producer.  I design backdrops and set-pieces.  I make enough to get by.  I work on the movies that are being pirated.  Please don't pirate because it hurts me too.  Not just the big corporation; the little guy is also affected.&quot;  Sort of putting a face on the other side.  Not sure how well it will do; but definitely a good tack.<br>
<br>
<br>
The whole &quot;They shouldn't charge so much if they want me to buy it&quot; argument also bothers me a whole lot for the theft of something that is not a necessity.  I agree that the prices of CDs are downright ridiculous.  However, that is the right of the music companies.  If it is too high; and not bought, it will filter it's way down to the bargain bins and/or the prices will eventually fall into line.  Or the whole industry will collapse and something else will arise.  [Heh.  Don't hold your breath on that though...]<br>
<br>
