 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bormwarrior>Borm Warrior</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mod in Kilt!</span><br>  Posts: 826<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/26/03 12:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=688.topic&index=17>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I hate the RIAA.  A lot.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'm not arguing in support of illegal downloading, just disagreeing with you that it necessarily causes a loss to the recording industry. If I had to pull a number out of my ass, I would say that about 10 to 15 percent of music downloaded online would have actually been purchased had people not been able to get it for free. I would guess the other 85 to 90 percent people like enough to download for free, but not enough to shell out 15 bucks for.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is where the downloaders mess things up for themselves. If there is a market for cheaper CDs then the industry would respond to it. It might take a while, but the laws of freemarket abhore the potential of lost sales. By stealing the music the thieves make sure that only people willing to pay $15 for the CD actually do. There is no market for $10 CDs or $5 CDs because the executives perceive that those potential customers will just download it for free.<br>
<br>
A central theme of economics is the pyramid. At the top is the few who are early adopters and will pay the highest price. At the bottom is the consumer who will onyl pay slightly over cost for the item. There is a sliding scale in between. The market watches that pyramid and adjusts as the consumers buy or do not buy. With music that market is modified by theft and so the bottom is never reached. At best we see used CDs and the &quot;Special&quot; compilations on the TV. Music has a short life span. It is completely fad driven so the market has a very short span.<br>
<br>
The point to all of these is that the theft of intellectual property has real and tangible costs that can be accounted for in a court of law. There is an entire generation about to learn this lesson the hard way and I am not unhappy to see that. I make my living with computer code and know what IP theft is all about. Everytime a music thief is punished is one less potential thief in my backyard a few years down the road.<br>
<br>
 <p>Warlord Borm, Veteran of Halas<br>
Member of Tribulation<br>
